<DOCNO> AP881223-0061 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
since philosopher leszek kolakowski broke 
his 20year exile to visit his homeland he has been toasted by the 
opposition and ignored by the communist party to which he once 
belonged 
hundreds of colleagues friends and students too young to have 
heard the young kolakowski openly criticize polish authorities have 
been filling auditoriums for the socalled kolakowski festival 
that began monday 
the lectures are the first in poland by the 61yearold 
kolakowski since he was expelled from warsaw university in 1968 
kolakowskis works are published in poland only by the underground 
press 
based at oxford university in england kolakowski has become one 
of the worlds leading philosophers winning fame for his 
threevolume history of marxist thought which focuses on what 
the author calls discrepancies between dogma and practice in 
communist countries 
the lectures have become a kolakowski festival and an 
important one for us said jerzy turowicz editor of the 
influential catholic weekly tygodnik powszechny in krakow 
about 500 students academics and leading members of the polish 
opposition squeezed together on the dark wooden benches of the main 
auditorium at warsaw university on monday to hear kolakowskis first 
lecture 
they gave kolakowski a twominute standing ovation when he stood 
up to speak 
kolakowski told the audience that when he left poland in 1968 
three secret police cars accompanied him to the airport while on 
this trip they havent paid him any attention 
on wednesday at an evening sponsored by the warsaw branch of the 
club of the catholic intelligentsia in the basement of a warsaw 
church kolakowski easily answered questions on the existence of 
devils and mystics and the link between philosophy and religion 
but when a question about the future of the banned trade union 
movement solidarity was raised kolakowski hesitated i have no 
recipe nothing is guaranteed he said 
polands communist party this year admitted wrongdoing in its 
purge of intellectuals and jews in 1968 and made clear that the 
flood of scholars who left the country then were welcome to return 
the granting of a visa to kolakowski visiting as a guest of the 
polish philosophical society is the most dramatic acceptance to 
date of that invitation kolakowski is expected to stay in poland 
about three weeks 
kolakowski began his academic career as a party member in the 
early 1950s but quickly clashed with orthodox communist ideologues 
in 1956 during a political thaw after stalins death known as 
the polish october kolakowski and a small group of communist 
intellectuals started straight talk a lively journal of critical 
marxist theory 
the young philosopher urged the party to strive for integral 
democracy for that view the party leadership branded kolakowski 
a revisionist and straight talk survived only a year before 
authorities banned it 
a 1966 university lecture on the polish october in which 
kolakowski accused authorities of breaking promises to the polish 
people cost the professor his party card 
the final blow to kolakowskis academic career came when the 
minister of education revoked his chair after the philosopher 
defended students who had participated in march 1968 unrest 
kolakowski soon left poland and joined other soviet bloc 
philosophers bloc forced into exile for their views including georg 
lukacs of hungary deported to romania in 1956 and ernst bloch who 
lost his chair at the university of leipzig in east germany in 1957 
he taught at universities in canada and the united states and 
finally settled at oxford university 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

