a newspaper today quoted a security source as 
saying investigators were taking very seriously a proiranian 
groups claim that it was responsible for the crash of a pan am 
jetliner in scotland 
the independent quoted the senior british security source as 
saying the group is thought to have sought revenge for the july 3 
downing of an iranian jetliner by a us warship in the persian gulf 
an anonymous caller to the associated press in london claimed 
thursday the guardians of the islamic revolution were responsible 
for wednesdays crash of pan am flight 103 which killed all 258 on 
board and 22 people on the ground 
irans foreign ministry today said the claim was a crude 
propaganda ploy designed to discredit iran and it denied 
involvement in the crash 
the official islamic republic news agency monitored in nicosia 
quoted an unidentified ministry spokesman as saying in tehran the 
scheme seems to be deliberately designed by foreign enemies of iran 
for specific purposes 
the independent quoted the unnamed source as identifying the 
group as a fundamentalist moslem group of lebanonbased islamic 
jihad fanatics 
investigators also focused on precrash threats of a terrorist 
strike 
in washington us officials said an anonymous caller to the 
us embassy in helsinki finland said dec 5 that a bomb would be 
planted aboard a pan am flight from frankfurt west germany to the 
united states within two weeks 
george churchillcoleman head of scotland yards antiterrorist 
branch opened an investigation thursday of the london stopover of 
flight 103 which originated in frankfurt and was bound for new york 
the sabotage theory focused on transfer of luggage between the 
boeing 727 that flew the frankfurtlondon leg and the boeing 747 
that took off for new york 
government and industry officials said it seemed clear the boeing 
747 broke apart in flight strewing blazing wreckage over the 
scottish village of lockerbie and surrounding hills 
such a sudden catastrophe would be consistent with flight 
controller reports that the cockpit sent no distress call as the 
plane having reached cruising altitude of 31000 feet disappeared 
from radar 
the times of london said the air accident investigation branch of 
britains transport department was examining wreckage under 
microscopes to measure the depth of indentations 
it said years of research showed that if a bomb is detonated in 
an aircraft fragments smash into their surroundings with 10 times 
more force than if the plane is downed for some other reason 
it said investigators were also looking for minute traces of 
burns or of explosive itself on seats and victims 
it is in many ways like a criminal investigation lockerbie 
police superintendent angus kennedy told reporters you have to 
preserve the scene we have to photograph bodies and bits and 
pieces it is a very long and very painstaking task 
other news reports quoted investigators as saying that the fact a 
few pieces of wreckage were found up to 80 miles from lockerbie 
suggested the plane had been blown apart by a powerful bomb 
