<TEXT>
the savannah river plants reactors which 
have been shut down by safety concerns could be restarted 
immediately if the nations defense demanded more nuclear weapons 
material the complexs manager said 
but plant manager john t lowe declined to say when he thought 
the plant in south carolina nearly 20 miles southeast of here would 
be restarted 
i think that remains to be defined lowe said in interviews 
published today in the augusta chronicle and the augusta herald 
there has been speculation that it would be six months or 12 
months i really think until the criteria are well defined 
its sheer speculation to pick a date 
i certainly think they the reactors can be restarted safely 
i think if the nation judged there was a need for the materials 
they could be restarted today 
lowe was interviewed thursday on the same day us energy 
secretary john herrington announced that ultrasonic testing would be 
used to check for possible cracks in reactor vessels that could 
delay srps restart until next summer 
all three savannah river reactors have been shut down since 
summer for safety upgrades and maintenance the shutdown is one of a 
number of problems plaguing the nations nuclear weapons production 
system including plants in fernald ohio and rocky flats colo 
some have expressed concern the shutdown at savannah river could 
harm the nations defense because the complex is americas only 
producer of tritium an isotope of hydrogen which is a critical 
element in hydrogen bombs and which deteriorates at the rate of 55 
percent a year 
lowe contended that the plant is safe to operate now and said 
the us department of energy wants to increase the complexs 
margin of safety the reactors have run safely for 35 years 
meeting the nations needs said lowe whose employer du pont 
runs the plant for doe theyve run without a nuclear incident 
that was an injury to anybody either on or off the plant and 
theyve been continuously upgraded over that time 
lowe said politics have played a role in the debate over the 
plants safety plant officials were criticized in congressional 
hearings earlier this year for not adequately reporting past safety 
problems 
certainly if you go back in time from 1950 to this year we 
have not only provided doe with notification of what we considered 
significant events but also a wrapup of what it meant lowe 
countered 
but with all the current attention there is an increasing 
emphasis from the doe to know things sooner and at a greater level 
of detail and so were working to develop a system and have that 
available to them 
some of its clearly congressional pressure 
du pont is wrapping up its involvement with the plant which 
dates back to the plants construction in the 1950s westinghouse is 
scheduled to take over operations of the facility april 1 
