<TEXT>
christmas eve will be silent night 
for almost 800 pirate radio stations slated to shut down 
indefinitely as part of a government plan to restructure 
broadcasting 
the centerright social democrat government has ordered the 
saturday closure while it evaluates offers from stations for control 
of 430 frequencies that will be available for local broadcast in 
1989 
final offers have to be submitted by jan 3 but the problem is 
the government hasnt said how long stations will be closed for 
said emidio rangel director of tsf a major commercial station that 
will close one day before the deadline to allow its employees to 
spend christmas with their families 
rangel said between 2000 and 3000 people could lose their jobs 
because of the closure 
pirate stations began broadcasting on the fm band in 1977 but 
with names like radio unforeseen and radio chaos most were amateur 
successive governments tolerated the pirates and the unregulated 
stations boomed 
tsf portugals most popular station among listeners in the 2545 
age group boasted a closing program friday with live interviews 
with president mario soares marathon star rosa mota and leading 
politicians 
the station set up in february this year with a capital of 
690000 has no plans to lay off its 75strong staff said tsf 
journalist luis marinho 
prime minister anibal cavaco silva is committed longterm to 
liberalizing the state national broadcasting monopoly but the 
government plans to hand over only one frequency to a national 
commercial network at a future date 
the government has been criticized for reallocating the local 
stations while leaving state and churchcontrolled national 
networks intact 
