<TEXT>
a bouquet of red tulips lay on the steps of 
syracuse universitys study center as students and teachers ended a 
memorial service friday for classmates killed in the pan am crash 
they hugged one another and wept clustered in small groups 
outside the gray stone church where the morning service was held 
and met at the elegant mansion that houses their school across the 
street 
they had such a passionate interest in life and a desire to 
make the world better malcolm ingrim a syracuse drama professor 
said as he remembered the six he taught and the other students 
killed in the crash wednesday night 
when all that is snuffed out in 30 seconds its impossible to 
make any sense of it he said its shattering 
the 35 syracuse students were among 258 people who died when the 
new yorkbound boeing 747 crashed in the scottish village of 
lockerbie on wednesday 
paul smith an english major from kennett square pa heard the 
news wednesday night while in a pub with friends 
it wasnt real i couldnt believe it he said 
smith shared a house with six friends including amy shapiro a 
student from stamford conn who died in the crash like others he 
knew just about all 270 students on the closeknit london program 
the students were chosen for the program for their academic 
ability and studied at the 19th century mansion on fashionable 
ladbroke grove with syracuse and london school of economics 
professors the term ended dec 17 and most had already gone home 
when the crash occurred 
after a friend got a call from the united states and went to the 
pub to tell them smith and the others raced to the study center to 
wait for news sometime past midnight they learned the students had 
made the flight and that there were no survivors 
it still isnt real you keep expecting amy to walk through the 
door he said his hands in his pockets and his eyes downcast 
asked what she was like he said she was the happiest person 
alive 
kristin huffmon a junior from madison nj said ms shapiro 
was studying photography and had always said halfjokingly that 
her dream was to work for national geographic magazine 
doesnt every photojournalism student want to work for national 
geographic that was amys joke said ms huffmon a political 
science major 
ingrim who is originally from london said three of his students 
theodora cohen miriam wolfe and nicole boulanger were planning 
to set up a theater troupe at school upon their return three 
others jason coker tim cardwell and turhan ergin also studied 
drama under him 
they were all extremely gifted he said when i see kids of 
such promise and energy i cannot imagine how the parents are 
feeling right now i just cant imagine 
at the memorial service at st johns church in west london 
vicar harold stringer and a local rabbi jacqueline tabick led the 
small group through prayers and hymns 
they read out the names of those lost and observed a moment of 
silence 
</TEXT>
