<TEXT>
the parliament on friday approved bills to 
encourge private ownership and foreign investment in an attempt to 
reverse four decades of state economic control 
the communist government pushed the two pieces of legislation 
which become law jan 1 to radically alter the structure of 
polands socialist economy 
polands 460member sejm or parliament unanimously approved the 
new law on economic activity which eliminates limits on the size of 
businesses that can be privately owned there were two abstentions 
the foreign investment bill drew two no votes and six 
abstentions the official pap news agency reported 
private business now accounts for about 6 percent of polands 
nonfarm economy but industry minister mieczyslaw wilczek calling 
the bills passage a historic breakthrough has said he hopes 
thousands of new businesses will open next year 
the new law on economic activity removes past discrimination 
against private ownership treating stateowned cooperative and 
private businesses the same for legal purposes 
private businesses previously were limited in size to 50 
employees and needed permission from administrative officials to 
operate businesses could be turned down if a local official deemed 
them unneeded or said they interfered with an existing state or 
cooperative monopoly 
but the new law removes any ceiling on the size of the work force 
and allows individuals cooperatives partnerships and limited 
liability companies to start and operate businesses as long as they 
comply with safety environmental and fire protection laws 
however 11 areas of activity such as weapons manufacture 
production and sales of pharmaceuticals and alcohol or operation of 
sea and air transport will require prior government licenses 
because they involve public safety 
firms are freed from the previous obligation to associate with 
industrial or professional groups 
despite the governments high hopes for the legislation there 
were some doubts 
to be able to invest in something one has to have 
something to invest said an article sunday in the weekly magazine 
wprost the majority of polish families spend their earnings on 
current consumption and cannot afford to start businesses 
only richer citizens have now gained an opportunity to show 
what they can do the article concludes 
the law on foreign investment combines and replaces two old laws 
one for investment by foreigners of polish descent and one for 
everyone else in both cases the rules are now easier 
a foreign investor must put up at least 20 percent of the 
startup cost of any business or joint venture and the business 
will be subject to a 40 percent income tax lower if the company 
produces for export 
unlike previous laws there are no requirements that majority 
control and local management be polish 
companies will have access to currency auctions where they can 
convert profits earned in zlotys to hard currency at market rates 
they also will be allowed to sell to poles in hard currency 
poland passed a foreigninvestment bill in 1986 but businesses 
considered its terms so unattractive that only about a dozen 
companies took advantage of it 
authorities hope that polands low wage scale and skilled work 
force will attract manufacturing and service facilities to serve 
other european countries 
the deputy prime minister ireneusz sekula presented the 
legislation to parliament thursday saying the laws would become the 
basis for freedom equality and competition in the economy 
departing from orthodox communist assumptions of an equal share 
in the wealth for all citizens he defined the states duty only as 
creating equal opportunity 
further possibilities should depend on peoples individual 
achievements he said this is the only way one should 
understand justice 
parliamentarian lucien stepien said that in the context of 
decades of stalinist governing the new laws might seem 
revolutionary 
but in reality he said they are just an attempt to get back 
to normal 
</TEXT>
