tone saturday when this community remembers 73 people most of them 
children who were crushed to death or suffocated at a christmas eve 
party 75 years ago 
the town council voted this week to hold a memorial service at 
the site where 57 children and 16 adults died they were killed in a 
human stampede after someone yelled a false fire alarm at a party 
sponsored by a union group at the height of a bitter strike 
i dont suppose it will ever heal said amateur historian 
jack foster 
at the time of the tragedy members of the western federation of 
miners had been on strike for 10 months over the calumet and hecla 
mining cos decision to switch from twoman drills to oneman 
drills the union said the new drill was unsafe 
in the weeks before the disaster two company guards chased a 
striker into a boardinghouse and fired gunshots killing two men 
three nonunion canadian miners were gunned down as they slept and 
miner and a guard were killed in another shootout 
on christmas eve the unions womens committee held a party for 
the children of striking miners on the second floor of calumets 
italian hall above a saloon 
while the party was under way witnesses said someone from the 
first floor stairwell shouted out a fire alarm children and adults 
raced to escape tripping over each other to get into the stairwell 
and out the only exit 
witnesses said the victims were crushed to death or suffocated 
before anyone realized what was happening 
i was so scared said lena rigotti an 88yearold hurley 
wis nursing home resident who survived the tragedy i told my 
sister stay with me and well get home i dont know how we ever 
made it 
nobody ever found out who sounded the false alarm foster said 
the disaster heightened tensions so much that national guard troops 
were ordered out to keep the peace and a congressional 
investigation was held 
the union called a halt to the strike that next spring 
bob pieti chairman of calumets downtown development authority 
said most residents would like to forget the tragedy but at 
saturdays nondemoninational prayer service and candlelight vigil 
the names of the victims will be read to remember the dead 
peggy germain a former calumet council member said the disaster 
still is a touchy subject 
the death certificates blame persons unknown and some of the 
stories are so insidious that i understand why over the years people 
in the town didnt want to talk about it she said 
