homeless activist dorothy king was found guilty 
friday of trespassing for occupying a vacant federally owned house 
last august with a group of homeless women and children 
king 36 was given a 10day suspended sentence she could have 
faced up to 180 days in jail and a fine of 999 
king who ran a shelter for the homeless that has since closed 
led a group of 14 women and 26 children from her shelter who spent a 
weekend in the house last august she was arrested after refusing an 
order to leave the other protesters left voluntarily 
the vacant building was the property of the us department of 
housing and urban development which had obtained it when the buyer 
defaulted on a federally backed mortgage 
on aug 16 one day after kings arrest hud agreed to make 55 
more homes available to qualified homeless shelter providers in 
colorado before then 14 homes had been made available to the 
colorado coalition for the homeless but king said they were all 
full 
king and her attorneys argued she acted under duress because of 
her commitment to denvers homeless she testified thursday that 
there was no shelter or afforadable housing in the area at the 
time of the protest and she didnt know what else to do 
they can arrest me if im a criminal for trying to find these 
people a house she recalled telling the arresting police officers 
prosecutors maintained the case was a clearcut one of 
trespassing 
you will hear that dorothy king works for the homeless she 
cares for the homeless she is deeply concerned about the 
homeless said assistant city attorney diane dash on thursday 
in the course of caring deeply about the homeless this defendant 
broke the law 
earlier in the week denver county court judge raymond satter 
denied kings motion to use a choice of evils defense which 
would have allowed her to be acquitted if the jury found she 
trespassed to prevent a greater evil in this case homelessness 
