us military forces in japan said friday they were 
halting all live firing training at an okinawa range where neighbors 
complained that bullets strayed into nearby residential areas 
the announcement by us forces japan did not refer directly to 
complaints that followed exercises oct 15 at a camp hansen firing 
range on the southern japanese island 
but it said senior us officials have expressed deep regret 
over recent incidents and have emphasized the respect and 
appreciation american military forces feel for the people of okinawa 
and their culture 
after local officials said nine bullets were reported found in a 
village opposite the ranges target area no one was reported 
injured but two foreign ministry officials went to okinawa last 
month to talk with us generals and inspect firing ranges 
the announcement also said that demonstration flights by f15 jet 
fighters at kadena air base also on okinawa were suspended 
indefinitely it gave no reason 
maj anthony rothfork spokeman for us forces in japan said 
safety regulations for other firing ranges had been reviewed 
permanent safety officers would be present for all live firing 
training the direction of firing would be restricted and safety 
education would be increased 
weeks after the firing range complaints a us navy ship fired 
practice shells that landed about 330 yards from a japanese coast 
guard vessel near the entrance to tokyo bay the navy immediately 
expressed regret and relieved the ships skipper of command 
but the foreign ministry lodged a protest with the us embassy 
and japanese newspaper editorials published blistering editorials 
about 64000 us troops are in japan under a security treaty 
about 35000 of them are stationed in okinawa an island of 12 
million people 
