<TEXT>
in the recent wave of south african theatrical 
productions exposing the oppression of apartheid the most popular 
is the surprisingly exuberant broadway musical sarafina 
television viewers who dont expect to be in new york anytime 
soon can get a taste of the show and a look behind the scenes in an 
nbc news special wednesday sarafina words of freedom songs 
of hope a onehour version of documentary maker nigel nobles 
featurelength film 
the film includes snippets of the incredibly infectious music 
composed by hugh masakela and the playwright mbongeni ngema and 
touching interviews with the talented cast of black south african 
teenagers who tell wrenching tales of repression beatings and 
deaths of loved ones but also express hope for the future 
id seen the play and had always wanted to do something to 
explain what apartheid did to people said nbc news senior 
executive producer paul greenberg cbs did a good show last year 
the documentary children of apartheid but the way these kids 
talk about it and act through the play they explain what happened 
to them in their own lives they describe their hope and after all 
that has happened to them they really want to go back 
the film is a departure for us because there are hardly any 
nbc people just the kids and the music greenberg said connie 
chung appears briefly to explain to viewers what they are about to 
see 
at one point ngema lectures his young charges about their 
mission in america the south african embassy has ambassadors 
here and ambassadors are people who speak for them the black 
people of south africa dont have an embassy here so this is the 
embassy and you are the ambassadors 
the kids have been immensely successful the show opened at 
lincoln center in october 1987 and moved to the cort theater on 
broadway it won rave reviews and has been selling out nightly 
the show is a loose flow of sketches about the lives of students 
at sowetos morris isaacson high school a school that prides itself 
on its political consciousness sarafina is a popular girl and one 
of the student leaders many of the musical numbers are joyous even 
funny but late in the play sarafinas incarceration and torture by 
police unseen gives fire to the other students commitment when 
she returns unbowed there is a climactic dance number in which the 
kids hurl themselves with deadly result at the military figures who 
double as the onstage band 
in an interview cast member dumisani dlamini describes the 
reality that inspired the scene i have seen things happening in 
front of my face i have seen my brothers dying and i have seen my 
heroes dying so how shall i sit down i have to stand and fight 
then ill be free 
theater in south africa at the moment plays a very important 
role says ngema we dont read a lot in the newspaper about 
what is happening in south africa and newspapers outside south 
africa cannot report everything they want to report so theater at 
this point in time has become the only voice left 
ngema recruited the youngsters from black townships and lived 
with the entire cast together in one small house for three months 
he got permission from their parents to take them 8000 miles away 
to new york by promising they would get a good education he 
explains that most south african black children dont attend school 
because the education they receive is poor and schools are subject 
to riots and police sweeps 
most americans probably cannot imagine how children raised under 
crushing oppression could attain broadway fame and still long to 
return to their homeland but the kids do 
i will go back to south africa because its where i belong 
too says dlamini its my home ill die in south africa 
thats what i think 
the climactic moment in the film comes when the children meet 
singer miriam makeba a spiritual leader for them despite her 27 
years in exile they are so overwhelmed by seeing her in person 
they cry and cling to her then break into song she is moved to 
tears 
i may die in exile today but i will die very happy knowing 
that you will continue to do all that i started doing makeba 
says spreading the message through your music and your lovely 
voices to the world telling them and showing them that we are a 
proud people and that we are in fact a struggling people and 
that we will win our independence and well be free like all other 
people in the world 
</TEXT>
