csx corp said friday it will sell its texas gas 
transmission co pipeline subsidiary and two related companies to 
transco energy co for 646 million 
the sale of texas gas which operates a 6000mile pipeline 
system extending from the gulf of mexico and east texas through 
eight other states is part of csxs continued restructuring 
transco agreed to pay 571 million for the natural gas pipeline 
operations plus an additional 75 million cash dividend to csx 
prior to closing 
transco is also assuming 256 million in debt bringing the total 
price tag to 902 million according to standard amp poors corp 
houstonbased transco through its transcontinental gas pipe line 
corp subsidiary operates a 10000mile natural gas transmission 
system serving primarily the eastern united states with a capacity 
of 31 billion cubic feet per day 
texas gas serves 92 gas distribution utilities and three 
interstate pipelines with mainline volumes averaging 600 billion 
cubic feet per year the company was purchased by csx in 1983 
george s slocum president and chief operating officer of 
transco said the texas gas purchase was part of the companys 
deemphasis of upstream oil and gas activities and renewed 
commitment to the natural gas pipeline business and gas related 
activities 
texas gas provides an excellent strategic fit with transcos 
businesses that will provide immediate and longterm benefits in 
operating efficiencies market opportunities and an attractive 
return on investment for transcos stockholders slocum said 
transco plans to finance the deal with up to 350 million of 
nonrecourse term debt through manufacturers hanover trust co 
and the sale of up to 200 million in preferred stock to corporate 
partners a private investor group officials said 
